        output='The provided material contains extensive cautionary language about the limitations of Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA, but it does not include a specific, separate discussion of why depreciation is excluded from these non-GAAP measures. The general rationale for all exclusions – including depreciation – is stated in the MD&A, and the broad warnings about non-GAAP measures are repeated in the non-GAAP disclosure. References to Connectivity segment satellite depreciation appear only in the description of GAAP cost of revenue, not in the non-GAAP discussion.\n\nBelow are the relevant excerpts, organized by topic.\n\n---\n\n### 1. Limitations of Adjusted EBITDA and cautionary language (broad warnings)\n\n**From the MD&A introduction to non-GAAP measures:**\n\n> Management believes that certain financial measures that are not presented in accordance with GAAP provide management and investors with useful supplemental information that provides a meaningful view of our financial condition and results of operations across periods by removing the impact of items that management believes do not directly reflect our ongoing operating performance. Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA are supplemental measures that are not required by or presented in accordance with GAAP. In evaluating our performance as measured by Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA, management recognizes and considers the limitations of these measures. Other companies in our industry may calculate Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA differently than we do or may not calculate them at all, limiting their usefulness as comparative measures. Because of these limitations, Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA should not be considered in isolation or as a substitute for net income (loss), income (loss) from operations, or any other measure calculated in accordance with GAAP, and should be considered together with our GAAP financial measures and the reconciliations to the corresponding most directly comparable GAAP financial measures set forth…\n\n**Reiterated in the dedicated non-GAAP disclosure (the chunk that defines the measures):**\n\n> …limiting their usefulness as comparative measures. Because of these limitations, Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA should not be considered in isolation or as a substitute for net income (loss), income (loss) from operations, or any other measure calculated in accordance with GAAP, and should be considered together with our GAAP financial measures and the reconciliations to the corresponding most directly comparable GAAP financial measures set forth [in the tables].\n\n---\n\n### 2. Why depreciation is excluded\n\nThe text does **not** offer a standalone statement like “Depreciation is a non-cash expense and is excluded because…” Instead, the sole rationale for excluding depreciation (and all other items) appears in the MD&A passage above:\n\n> …by removing the impact of items that management believes do not directly reflect our ongoing operating performance.\n\nDepreciation is listed among the items removed from net income to arrive at Adjusted EBITDA, and from segment operating income to arrive at Segment Adjusted EBITDA. The definitions are:\n\n- **Adjusted EBITDA**: net income (loss) excluding depreciation and amortization, share-based compensation, impairment, restructuring charges, interest expense, interest income, other income (expense), net, and provision for income taxes.\n- **Segment Adjusted EBITDA**: segment income (loss) from operations excluding depreciation and amortization, share-based compensation, restructuring charges, and impairment.\n\nThese are described as “key performance measures” that management uses “to assess our financial performance as well as for internal planning and forecasting purposes,” and are considered “meaningful performance measures for investors to evaluate our operating performance and to compare the financial results…” No further